Note:
Runtime semaphore API — the public counting-semaphore object for the Runa
runtime concurrency system.

This is the runtime-facing object layer. The actual counting mechanism is the
completed cross-platform synchronization facade (sync_core), which itself
delegates to the per-architecture OS semaphore / futex primitives. This module
does NOT re-implement the semaphore; it wraps the sync_core handle in a runtime
RuntimeSemaphore object and adds the semantics a runtime contract requires that
the raw facade does not provide:

  - COUNTING PERMITS: a semaphore admits up to its current permit count of
    concurrent acquirers. semaphore_acquire blocks until a permit is available
    and consumes it; semaphore_release returns a permit, potentially waking a
    blocked acquirer. semaphore_try_acquire takes a permit only when one is
    immediately available, never blocking.
  - POISONING: a counting semaphore needs no poison flag to function, but the
    flag is carried here for contract symmetry with the other synchronization
    modules and to let a permit holder surface "a holder corrupted the state
    this semaphore guards access to" without unwinding. Later acquirers still
    obtain a permit (admission is still needed to inspect/repair the state) but
    are told SEM_ERR_POISONED so they can decide whether to recover or abort.
  - STANDARDIZED STATUS CODES: every entry point returns a SEM_* status so
    callers branch on a single, documented contract rather than the facade's
    raw 1/0 platform results.

RuntimeSemaphore layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  handle    — the sync_core sem_ptr (the real counting semaphore)
    offset 8:  poisoned  — 0 healthy, 1 poisoned
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory

Note: RuntimeSemaphore object layout
Constant RT_SEM_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE as Integer is 0
Constant RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED as Integer is 8

Note: Status codes returned by the runtime semaphore API
Constant SEM_OK as Integer is 0
Constant SEM_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant SEM_ERR_POISONED as Integer is 0 minus 2
Constant SEM_ERR_WAIT_FAILED as Integer is 0 minus 3
Constant SEM_ERR_BUSY as Integer is 0 minus 4

Process called "semaphore_new" takes initial_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Create a runtime semaphore object with a starting permit count. Mechanism
    (the OS counting semaphore) comes from sync_core; this layer adds the poison
    flag and a stable object identity callers hold.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Reject a negative initial_count by returning 0 — permit counts are
    non-negative by definition and the facade cannot represent a negative seed.
    Allocate the 16-byte RuntimeSemaphore, create the underlying sync_core
    semaphore with initial_count, store its handle, and initialize the poison
    flag to healthy (0). On any allocation/creation failure, release whatever
    was acquired and return 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One small allocation plus one sync_core semaphore_create (which allocates
    its own 16-byte control block and an OS semaphore). Cold path: done once
    per semaphore.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Negative initial_count and any failure return 0 (NULL); callers MUST check
    before use.
    @End Security_Scope

    If initial_count is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let s be proc allocate from Memory with RT_SEM_SIZE
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let handle be proc semaphore_create from Sync with initial_count
    If handle is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with s
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE, handle
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return s
End Process

Process called "semaphore_acquire" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block until a permit is available, consume it, then report whether the
    guarded state is trustworthy. The permit is taken even when poisoned because
    the caller still needs admission to inspect or repair the inconsistent data.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate the blocking acquire to sync_core semaphore_wait. If that fails to
    report success, no permit was taken and we return SEM_ERR_WAIT_FAILED. Once
    a permit is held, return SEM_ERR_POISONED when the poison flag is set (the
    permit is still held and must be released), otherwise SEM_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core semaphore_wait (fast permit decrement on the available path;
    OS wait only when no permit is available) plus two field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns SEM_ERR_NULL without touching memory. When SEM_OK or
    SEM_ERR_POISONED is returned a permit IS held and the caller owns the
    obligation to release it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc semaphore_wait from Sync with handle
    If r is not equal to 1:
        Return SEM_ERR_WAIT_FAILED
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return SEM_OK
End Process

Process called "semaphore_try_acquire" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Non-blocking acquire for callers that must make progress rather than wait
    for a permit to become available.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core semaphore_try_wait. A non-success result means no
    permit was immediately available (SEM_ERR_BUSY). On success, surface poison
    state exactly as semaphore_acquire does so the held/poison contract is
    identical on both paths.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core semaphore_try_wait (single permit-decrement attempt, never
    blocks) plus field loads.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns SEM_ERR_NULL. A permit is held only when SEM_OK or
    SEM_ERR_POISONED is returned.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE
    Let r be proc semaphore_try_wait from Sync with handle
    If r is not equal to 1:
        Return SEM_ERR_BUSY
    End If

    Let poisoned be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED
    If poisoned is not equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_POISONED
    End If
    Return SEM_OK
End Process

Process called "semaphore_release" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Return a permit. Must be called exactly once per successful acquire
    (including the SEM_ERR_POISONED acquire, which still holds a permit) so the
    permit count stays balanced.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core semaphore_signal, which increments the permit count
    and wakes a blocked acquirer if one is present. Return SEM_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core semaphore_signal (user-space increment on the uncontended
    path; a single OS wake when waiters are present).
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns SEM_ERR_NULL. Releasing more permits than were acquired
    raises the permit ceiling and is a caller logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE
    proc semaphore_signal from Sync with handle
    Return SEM_OK
End Process

Process called "semaphore_is_poisoned" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report whether a previous permit holder flagged the guarded data as
    inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the poison flag (1 poisoned, 0 healthy).
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Pure read.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED
End Process

Process called "semaphore_poison" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Mark the semaphore poisoned. A permit holder that detects an unrecoverable
    failure in the guarded state calls this before releasing so later acquirers
    are warned the data may be inconsistent.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding a permit so the flag is published before the
    next acquirer observes it.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED, 1
    Return SEM_OK
End Process

Process called "semaphore_clear_poison" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Clear the poison flag after a caller has repaired the guarded state,
    returning the semaphore to normal service.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the poison flag to 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field store.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Should be called while holding a permit, after the inconsistent state has
    actually been repaired.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_POISONED, 0
    Return SEM_OK
End Process

Process called "semaphore_destroy" takes s as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release the OS semaphore and free the runtime object. Must not be called
    while permits are still outstanding to a blocked acquirer.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Delegate to sync_core semaphore_destroy (which frees the facade control
    block and the OS semaphore), then deallocate the RuntimeSemaphore object.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One sync_core semaphore_destroy plus one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null object returns SEM_ERR_NULL. Destroying a semaphore with blocked
    waiters is a logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If s is equal to 0:
        Return SEM_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let handle be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with s, RT_SEM_OFF_HANDLE
    proc semaphore_destroy from Sync with handle
    proc deallocate from Memory with s
    Return SEM_OK
End Process
